list.item:
def is clearly intended to provide a prose description of a
                            meaning within a sense element and should not appear in any
                            other context;

@subtype should be added to form and is equivalent to @type of the
                            refined element e.g. form[@type=”paradigm”][@subtype=”full”]≡
                            paradigm[@type=”full”]

an entry can have several paradigms, where it would be useful to have @subtype on form (currently not allowed). Examples where this would be needed are e.g.:
if a verb inflects according to two different conjugation classes (two iTypes)
one “paradigm” giving just one or two forms for humans to know what the paradigm is, and one for machines, containing the complete inflectional paradigm
@resp should be somewhere there for stuff that we add to the dictionary that’s not in the source (e.g. full paradigm)
what do we use for referencing external paradigms? @ana seems a bit abusive(?)
hiding extra stuff with rendition mechanisms

proposal: remove text node from the content model of xr, but add
                            model.entryPart (in order to complement / put some additional context
                            for xr)

@type is a mandatory attribute on ref for a lexical
                                reference. Its default value is “lexical” and can be supersede (or
                                complemented by means of @subtype)

typing entries: to be discussed - check literature (Axel); mandatory??
                            (keep in mind dictionaries of proverbs; collocation dictionaries;
                            dictionaries of idioms)
